00:13:37,514 --> 00:13:40,797
people do where it's just a sweatshop, rows and rows and rows of monitors.

240
00:13:42,262 --> 00:13:44,684
Collaboration space, they had a ton of space,

241
00:13:44,704 --> 00:13:46,425
so they could have a lot of collaboration space.

242
00:13:47,045 --> 00:13:49,728
And here, again, they tried this hybrid layout

243
00:13:49,808 --> 00:13:53,050
where each game team has a physically distinct area,

244
00:13:53,851 --> 00:13:56,233
as do the central services folks.

245
00:13:56,993 --> 00:14:00,376
But crucially, within that area, the arrangement

246
00:14:00,456 --> 00:14:04,779
was non-standardized and was driven by the folks

247
00:14:04,819 --> 00:14:07,482
at the top, the general managers of those games.

248
00:14:09,619 --> 00:14:11,861
Make sure that you note that was driven by leaderships,

249
00:14:11,921 --> 00:14:13,783
because that will come back in a minute.

250
00:14:14,283 --> 00:14:15,765
So what was the overall approach?

251
00:14:16,305 --> 00:14:18,067
Basically, Zynga is trying very, very hard

252
00:14:18,127 --> 00:14:19,348
to make everything fun and playful.

253
00:14:19,969 --> 00:14:22,851
The idea, of course, is that if the employees are having fun,

254
00:14:22,891 --> 00:14:24,753
it'll be easier for them to make more fun games

255
00:14:24,793 --> 00:14:27,256
for the customers, and sometimes this worked,

256
00:14:27,536 --> 00:14:30,319
and sometimes it resulted in cognitive dissonance

257
00:14:30,399 --> 00:14:33,382
and forced fun and lots of hate.

258
00:14:33,744 --> 00:14:37,285
So this can be absolute cultural poison,

259
00:14:37,565 --> 00:14:39,645
but it wasn't the only challenge that Zynga faced

260
00:14:39,685 --> 00:14:40,966
with the approach that they chose.

261
00:14:43,066 --> 00:14:45,387
It's really expensive to do things like this.

262
00:14:45,487 --> 00:14:50,228
And when revenues turn down, the ball pit starts to look goofy.

263
00:14:51,808 --> 00:14:54,969
Scalability, there's only a certain number

264
00:14:54,989 --> 00:14:56,730
of people that can fit on the water slide.

265
00:14:57,430 --> 00:14:58,990
When you get more people, you can't

266
00:14:59,030 --> 00:14:59,990
make the water slide any bigger.

267
00:15:00,719 --> 00:15:03,760
And importantly, as we were saying before about management

268
00:15:03,800 --> 00:15:06,100
being able to call the shots on how things moved around,

269
00:15:06,841 --> 00:15:10,502
this interferes with humans' nesting impulse.

270
00:15:10,582 --> 00:15:13,563
People want to have some degree of agency over their space.

271
00:15:14,183 --> 00:15:15,364
We see this over and over again.

272
00:15:15,404 --> 00:15:19,685
And this is actually a pretty commonly mentioned issue

273
00:15:19,845 --> 00:15:21,066
in white papers and studies.

274
00:15:22,126 --> 00:15:24,047
People want to have some control over their space.

275
00:15:24,087 --> 00:15:26,308
When you take that away from them, it's not good.

276
00:15:27,464 --> 00:15:30,025
it just sort of increases their degree of nervousness.

277
00:15:30,085 --> 00:15:33,567
So a lot of the sort of hipster ad agencies

278
00:15:33,587 --> 00:15:35,787
where it's like, well, you don't even have a computer,

279
00:15:35,847 --> 00:15:39,009
you just take a notepad and draw on it

280
00:15:39,109 --> 00:15:41,790
and sit in the corner and lie on the fake grass

281
00:15:41,850 --> 00:15:42,970
or whatever it is that we've got,

282
00:15:44,030 --> 00:15:47,592
that doesn't often work out.

283
00:15:48,272 --> 00:15:49,232
If you're particularly interested,

284
00:15:49,252 --> 00:15:52,714
there's a white paper by guys called Fleming and Sturdy,

285
00:15:53,314 --> 00:15:55,755
which is called Being Yourself in the Electronic Sweatshop.

286
00:15:56,212 --> 00:16:03,046
new forms of normative control. That's in Human Relations, which is an academic journal.

287
00:16:03,387 --> 00:16:06,533
I'll give you more information on that if you want it at some point.

288
00:16:08,267 --> 00:16:10,869
But so let's take a look at a second space.

289
00:16:11,690 --> 00:16:13,111
Space number two is Three Rings.

290
00:16:13,631 --> 00:16:15,693
If you've never been to a meeting or a party there,

291
00:16:16,293 --> 00:16:17,254
this place is really unique.

292
00:16:17,654 --> 00:16:21,156
The studio is owned by Sega now, but when they opened this office,

293
00:16:21,196 --> 00:16:21,897
it was an indie.

294
00:16:22,037 --> 00:16:24,799
And they started to take a really dramatic approach

295
00:16:24,879 --> 00:16:27,581
to one of these classic small developer problems of how

296
00:16:27,601 --> 00:16:29,002
to build out a white box.

297
00:16:30,423 --> 00:16:33,485
They had a giant Class B loft, really common.

298
00:16:34,395 --> 00:16:37,257
You probably have one if you have worked at a small developer.

299
00:16:37,277 --> 00:16:38,697
It's just an empty white box.

300
00:16:39,117 --> 00:16:45,039
It was about, I guess, 1 10th of a football pitch, so not huge.

301
00:16:45,600 --> 00:16:49,581
And key to this is that what you're about to see here,

302
00:16:49,601 --> 00:16:54,383
this steampunk submarine thing, is half of their office,

303
00:16:54,863 --> 00:16:58,284
the back half, which was completely redesigned.

304
00:16:58,324 --> 00:17:02,446
The front half stayed very similar to its original build.

305
00:17:03,311 --> 00:17:04,692
This is intentionally cozy.

306
00:17:04,732 --> 00:17:06,833
So they actually had quite a bit more space

307
00:17:06,893 --> 00:17:10,074
than they wound up slicing up and giving to the employees

308
00:17:10,714 --> 00:17:13,455
on purpose, trying to sort of increase

309
00:17:13,555 --> 00:17:17,137
the effort for collaboration by packing everybody

310
00:17:17,197 --> 00:17:18,498
into smaller spaces.

311
00:17:18,538 --> 00:17:19,558
So that's quite intentional.

312
00:17:20,158 --> 00:17:23,140
And they divided their space up into these small group

313
00:17:23,180 --> 00:17:26,001
work rooms, little pods with four or five folks in them

314
00:17:26,461 --> 00:17:29,442
that would be a department working on a game,

315
00:17:30,643 --> 00:17:32,023
but not giant.

316
00:17:32,958 --> 00:17:35,100
one giant team of 35 people.

317
00:17:35,520 --> 00:17:38,182
So even small companies, especially in San Francisco,

318
00:17:38,222 --> 00:17:39,843
wound up in this perk arms race.

319
00:17:40,384 --> 00:17:41,685
According to Three Rings, however,

320
00:17:41,885 --> 00:17:44,006
it was practically impossible to hire engineers

321
00:17:44,026 --> 00:17:45,707
at this point, and the office actually

322
00:17:45,747 --> 00:17:47,609
was a key marketing tool for them.

323
00:17:48,109 --> 00:17:50,411
So despite superficial similarities,

324
00:17:50,451 --> 00:17:51,912
this is really a very different use

325
00:17:52,112 --> 00:17:54,754
of architectural playfulness than what we saw with SingIt.

326
00:17:55,575 --> 00:17:57,176
It's also important to note that though

327
00:17:57,196 --> 00:17:59,538
the steampunk aesthetic was completely pervasive

328
00:17:59,578 --> 00:18:00,738
in the front half of the office,

329
00:18:01,250 --> 00:18:05,272
This was definitely the party in the back portion of the Three Rings office mullet.

330
00:18:06,593 --> 00:18:12,015
There's a much more straightforward space on the other side of a wall that you can't see here.

331
00:18:12,416 --> 00:18:17,398
And that has largely become home to the business type functions versus the design and the artwork,

332
00:18:18,078 --> 00:18:19,359
which are going on in the submarine.

333
00:18:19,699 --> 00:18:24,862
And that's maybe the most literal case of architectural determinism that I have ever seen.

334
00:18:25,422 --> 00:18:29,885
And it does affect the employees, and we'll see how in slide or two.

335
00:18:30,396 --> 00:18:32,837
So here's how Three Rings approached those big game

336
00:18:32,857 --> 00:18:34,198
development workspace issues.

337
00:18:34,578 --> 00:18:35,879
Very different to what Zynga did.

338
00:18:37,560 --> 00:18:39,642
And they did a couple of things that a giant corporation really

339
00:18:39,682 --> 00:18:40,142
can't do.

340
00:18:40,202 --> 00:18:42,183
Well, for example, they knew that they

341
00:18:42,203 --> 00:18:43,624
weren't going to have a huge noise problem,

342
00:18:43,664 --> 00:18:45,645
because they had a relatively good sized space

343
00:18:45,685 --> 00:18:46,846
and very few employees.

344
00:18:47,346 --> 00:18:48,667
That's one way to solve that problem,

345
00:18:48,687 --> 00:18:51,048
but it's not a call you can necessarily make.

346
00:18:51,649 --> 00:18:52,970
For visual privacy, they actually

347
00:18:53,030 --> 00:18:56,532
partitioned up their workspace and faced the desks

348
00:18:56,672 --> 00:18:58,353
towards walls and partitions.

349
00:18:58,752 --> 00:19:02,936
in order to avoid the problem of having you looking out at, you know, a sea of monitors

350
00:19:02,977 --> 00:19:04,458
with visual chaos behind them.

351
00:19:04,858 --> 00:19:09,863
Their collaboration spaces, actually as you can see on their layout here, practically

352
00:19:10,084 --> 00:19:15,349
all of the office space in this area is designed as a sort of small, informal collaborative

353
00:19:15,409 --> 00:19:15,769
space.

354
00:19:16,270 --> 00:19:17,311
And then they also have a...

355
00:19:17,987 --> 00:19:22,047
a secret library room that you enter through a bookcase that

356
00:19:22,107 --> 00:19:23,068
was a conference.

357
00:19:23,168 --> 00:19:24,768
Really, this office space is tremendous.

358
00:19:24,828 --> 00:19:28,089
So pardon me if I'm just like goofy about it.

359
00:19:28,289 --> 00:19:30,989
The light level was very clever here.

360
00:19:31,029 --> 00:19:33,330
They have these big curtains that you

361
00:19:33,350 --> 00:19:36,730
can see over their large loft windows.

362
00:19:37,050 --> 00:19:39,871
And they have custom made light fixture covers

363
00:19:39,931 --> 00:19:41,651
that mute the fluorescent lights.

364
00:19:41,851 --> 00:19:44,532
So you can kind of adjust the lights in a way.

365
00:19:45,872 --> 00:19:51,417
a much more granular way than you saw in a space like Zynga or in a lot of Class B office space.

366
00:19:52,158 --> 00:19:59,945
And here they have their teams in separate spaces, but they kind of have a sort of miniature version of the hybrid

367
00:20:00,265 --> 00:20:05,610
with individual groups inside teams parked together to encourage collaboration with them.

368
00:20:06,410 --> 00:20:11,155
Unfortunately, they actually only had one private collaborative space.

369
00:20:11,742 --> 00:20:16,304
but a lot of this space was available for public collaboration.

370
00:20:16,804 --> 00:20:21,066
So the TLDR is that through salesmanship and smart design and luck,

371
00:20:21,386 --> 00:20:24,607
Three Rings was able to give themselves a completely unique environment

372
00:20:25,088 --> 00:20:28,269
that functioned as a calling card that explained how the company works

373
00:20:28,669 --> 00:20:31,450
and how they think of themselves as you walk through it,

374
00:20:31,731 --> 00:20:33,091
as a visitor or an employee.

375
00:20:33,751 --> 00:20:36,633
The major issues that arose, though, are something you probably have already guessed.

376
00:20:37,210 --> 00:20:39,652
Once you have a steampunk submarine in your office,

377
00:20:39,872 --> 00:20:43,374
your company is kind of like about having a steampunk

378
00:20:43,395 --> 00:20:44,355
submarine in your office.

379
00:20:45,496 --> 00:20:49,378
And that introduces a bunch of risks around changing tastes,

380
00:20:49,459 --> 00:20:49,979
for example.

381
00:20:49,999 --> 00:20:53,481
You're maybe not always going to want a steampunk submarine.

382
00:20:55,102 --> 00:20:58,605
Packing all of these people into tight spaces on purpose

383
00:20:58,685 --> 00:21:02,167
can obviously introduce some issues as well.

384
00:21:03,108 --> 00:21:05,049
And the fact that you're sort of basically

385
00:21:05,169 --> 00:21:06,330
stuck with what you've got.

386
00:21:07,448 --> 00:21:11,211
Tom Schofield, who is one of the principals at Three Rings, told me,

387
00:21:12,251 --> 00:21:16,755
the way we thought of it was, anything works in here as long as it fits in a steampunk submarine.

388
00:21:18,276 --> 00:21:22,960
So it's a little bit deterministic, but obviously there's some big upside.

389
00:21:23,320 --> 00:21:28,604
So the final case study that I'm going to take a look at looks at a totally different type of space.

390
00:21:28,624 --> 00:21:32,627
This is a very different space, a very different budget, and a totally different set of requirements.

391
00:21:33,078 --> 00:21:38,401
This is New York's Waka Waka, which is a game development co-working space and incubator

392
00:21:39,041 --> 00:21:43,603
in the trendy Lower East Side, located in a former storefront tattoo parlor.

393
00:21:44,723 --> 00:21:49,205
This space was inherited and tweaked, but in a lot of ways it's the same type of space

394
00:21:49,245 --> 00:21:52,286
that it was when it was an art gallery a few tenants ago.

395
00:21:53,086 --> 00:21:58,888
It's a small open room, and it's long and narrow, which rules out a lot of the desk

396
00:21:58,968 --> 00:22:00,509
layouts that we talked about before.

397
00:22:01,175 --> 00:22:08,620
Though without any real permanent walls, it's quite flexible and it has a second story and a tiny little yard that can be configured in a few different ways.

398
00:22:09,661 --> 00:22:16,445
So, check this out. Even a 2,000 square foot office makes an amenity play in its own way.

399
00:22:16,485 --> 00:22:17,886
So that maybe tells us something.

400
00:22:18,446 --> 00:22:22,489
People like to say that they don't care about perks that much, like this cool little backyard.

401
00:22:22,849 --> 00:22:26,712
But again, we see a significant effort to maximize the available resources.

402
00:22:27,206 --> 00:22:29,729
Waka Waka doesn't have much furniture in it at all,

403
00:22:29,789 --> 00:22:33,232
but what is there is high quality and extremely stylish.

404
00:22:34,073 --> 00:22:37,196
Flexibility and minimalist chic are just overflowing here.

405
00:22:37,757 --> 00:22:40,820
And this sort of underscores the aspirational aspect

406
00:22:41,040 --> 00:22:42,161
of workspace design.

407
00:22:45,345 --> 00:22:47,887
Is it showing two different things or something?

408
00:22:48,967 --> 00:22:51,188
All right, cool.

409
00:22:51,208 --> 00:22:53,589
So we don't actually really design a workspace

410
00:22:53,629 --> 00:22:56,591
around our employees so much as we

411
00:22:57,051 --> 00:22:58,992
create a space that looks like it's already

412
00:22:59,072 --> 00:23:01,773
home to the type of people that we want working in it.

413
00:23:02,433 --> 00:23:06,315
And whether that's a feature or a bug,

414
00:23:06,375 --> 00:23:08,916
we kind of, that's up to us to figure out.

415
00:23:09,464 --> 00:23:11,785
So how did Waka Waka address the big issues?

416
00:23:12,466 --> 00:23:14,547
It's harder for them than for Three Rings or Zynga

417
00:23:14,567 --> 00:23:16,968
because they couldn't really choose much about how

418
00:23:16,988 --> 00:23:19,730
their space is laid out, about what materials it's made out of.

419
00:23:20,210 --> 00:23:23,131
It's really noisy if there are a lot of people in there.

420
00:23:23,612 --> 00:23:25,313
The whole thing is made out of polished concrete.

421
00:23:25,353 --> 00:23:26,893
Now they've done what they can about that.

422
00:23:27,034 --> 00:23:29,615
As you can see, even the desk is made out

423
00:23:29,655 --> 00:23:31,136
of noise baffling material.

424
00:23:31,936 --> 00:23:34,418
And they've got a bunch of noise baffles hanging on the wall.

425
00:23:34,438 --> 00:23:35,478
So they are smart about it.

426
00:23:36,619 --> 00:23:38,160
As far as visual privacy goes.

427
00:23:39,026 --> 00:23:40,147
there's really only two options.

428
00:23:40,167 --> 00:23:42,789
You could have everybody facing directly into a white wall.

429
00:23:43,810 --> 00:23:44,190
Not great.

430
00:23:44,730 --> 00:23:46,772
Or you could have everyone sort of looking

431
00:23:46,792 --> 00:23:48,773
at a maximum of one other person.

432
00:23:49,574 --> 00:23:50,474
And that's what they did.

433
00:23:51,856 --> 00:23:54,377
For a collaboration space, this is kind of tricky.

434
00:23:54,678 --> 00:23:56,579
The studio amenities and infrastructure

435
00:23:56,639 --> 00:23:59,461
are shared between everyone that's in there.

436
00:24:00,182 --> 00:24:01,723
It's kind of a big open space.

437
00:24:01,743 --> 00:24:03,044
They have a little area in the back

438
00:24:03,064 --> 00:24:05,666
that you can sort of see there that has a couch.

439
00:24:05,966 --> 00:24:06,066
And

440
00:24:07,150 --> 00:24:10,212
Their backyard is also sort of an ad hoc collaboration space,

441
00:24:10,272 --> 00:24:11,333
as is their downstairs.

442
00:24:11,413 --> 00:24:13,794
But ultimately, there aren't very many walls.

443
00:24:15,115 --> 00:24:16,776
So there's a limit to what you can do.

444
00:24:17,836 --> 00:24:20,518
Now, the layout, of course, can change.

445
00:24:20,678 --> 00:24:22,679
Other than getting new giant desks,

446
00:24:23,279 --> 00:24:24,400
they can switch things up.

447
00:24:24,760 --> 00:24:27,141
But at the end of the day, there's

448
00:24:27,181 --> 00:24:28,742
not much solitude that's possible.

449
00:24:29,685 --> 00:24:33,307
So what the core of WakaWaka's workspace approach

450
00:24:33,367 --> 00:24:35,328
is about allowing small independent teams

451
00:24:35,388 --> 00:24:37,349
to work in close proximity to each other

452
00:24:37,989 --> 00:24:40,590
and share facilities that they could otherwise never afford.

453
00:24:41,391 --> 00:24:43,672
This office signifies to potential coworkers

454
00:24:43,712 --> 00:24:45,553
and to those visiting that the people who work here

455
00:24:45,673 --> 00:24:48,454
understand the indie game aesthetic through and through.

456
00:24:49,075 --> 00:24:51,916
It's sparse, but precise, and above all else,

457
00:24:52,296 --> 00:24:54,778
it's elegant in both functional and visual design.

458
00:24:55,018 --> 00:24:57,399
So this works to attract like-minded collaborators.

459
00:24:58,199 --> 00:25:01,482
And it immediately tells a compelling story to, for example,

460
00:25:01,662 --> 00:25:04,845
visiting publishers who are attending meetings with the developers that are based here.

461
00:25:05,545 --> 00:25:08,027
This approach definitely comes with some real challenges, however.

462
00:25:08,507 --> 00:25:09,528
The space is small,

463
00:25:12,551 --> 00:25:16,574
and there's no real layout choices.

464
00:25:17,314 --> 00:25:20,197
So the various privacy concerns are magnified tremendously.

465
00:25:20,537 --> 00:25:21,998
There's also the question of scale.

466
00:25:22,499 --> 00:25:25,321
If you succeed here, you kind of have to leave.

467
00:25:26,241 --> 00:25:28,463
So this randomizes the balance of the people in the space,

468
00:25:28,503 --> 00:25:30,664
and that can be a huge issue in a workspace

469
00:25:30,704 --> 00:25:32,846
that's only got about a dozen other folks in there.

470
00:25:33,907 --> 00:25:36,789
The materials we talked about, it's all polished concrete,

471
00:25:36,850 --> 00:25:39,171
so they couldn't really do too much with that,

472
00:25:40,032 --> 00:25:41,133
but they kind of ran with it

473
00:25:41,213 --> 00:25:42,694
rather than trying to fight against it.

474
00:25:43,875 --> 00:25:46,057
It's TBD how well that works out.

475
00:25:47,078 --> 00:25:48,539
And then on top of the challenge

476
00:25:48,559 --> 00:25:49,920
of people scaling out of the office.

477
00:25:50,250 --> 00:25:54,831
You really have to trust the curation instincts of the people

478
00:25:54,851 --> 00:25:55,691
that run this space.

479
00:25:55,731 --> 00:25:58,612
Now, this particular workspace is run by game business

480
00:25:58,652 --> 00:25:59,052
veterans.

481
00:25:59,472 --> 00:26:01,092
But if that's not always the case,

482
00:26:01,152 --> 00:26:04,333
then you could wind up in here with whoever

483
00:26:04,353 --> 00:26:06,353
they were able to get to fill the seats in order

484
00:26:06,393 --> 00:26:07,613
to pay the rent.

485
00:26:08,173 --> 00:26:10,894
So at last, here are the tweetable takeaways.

486
00:26:11,614 --> 00:26:12,954
I'm going to put them up there one by one.

487
00:26:13,014 --> 00:26:15,935
So maybe wait till the end if you want to take a picture.

